{"title_page": "Phlomis bourgaei", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of flowering plants in the sage family Lamiaceae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Phlomis bourgaei-Clapiers-7645~2020 03 27.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Phlomis bourgaei'', flowers and leaves\n|image_upright = 0.66\n|genus = Phlomis\n|species = bourgaei\n|authority = [[Edmond Boissier|Boiss.]]\n|synonyms = \n* ''Phlomis schwarzii'' P.H.Davis\n}}\n'''''Phlomis bourgaei''''', the '''puckered gray-green Turkish phlomis''',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ogden|first=Scott|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_w_9TBFiSqgC&pg=PA59|title=Waterwise Plants for Sustainable Gardens: 200 Drought-Tolerant Choices for all Climates|last2=Ogden|first2=Lauren Springer|date=2011-11-03|publisher=Timber Press|isbn=978-1-60469-336-2|language=en}}</ref> is a [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] Lamiaceae, [[native plant|native]] to East [[Aegean Islands]] to South West [[Turkey]].<ref name=\"Filippi2007\">{{cite book |last=Filippi |first=Olivier |date=2007 |title=Pour un jardin sans arrosage (For a garden without irrigation) |location=Arles |publisher=Actes Sud |page=154 |language=fr |isbn=978-2-7427-6730-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Stasher2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://noellemace.blogspot.com/2019/01/phlomis-fruticosa-bourgaei.html|title=''Phlomis fruticosa'' 'Bourgaei'|last=Stasher|date=2019-01-26|website=Stasher|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Botanical name#Binary name|specific epithet]] ''bourgaei'' is a [[Patronym (taxonomy)#Naming process|taxonomic patronym]] honouring the French botanical traveller [[Eug\u00e8ne Bourgeau]] (1813-1877), who collected in [[Anatolia]], [[North Africa]], and [[North America]]. \n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Phlomis bourgaei-MNHN-P-P00738090.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Herbarium specimen of ''Phlomis bourgaei'', collected by Eug\u00e8ne Bourgeau in 1860.]]\nIt is a [[shrub]], [[evergreen]], growing to {{convert|1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} tall by {{convert|80|cm|ft|0|abbr=on}} wide. The foliage shows a pronounced [[seasonal dimorphism]]. In winter and spring, the large, gray-green leaves develop horizontally to maximize [[photosynthesis]] during the growing period. In summer, after the flowering, the big leaves fall and the plant then produces a new generation of smaller, undulated leaves, compressed against each other along the stems to reduce the area of sun exposure and limit [[evapotranspiration]]. These new leaves are covered with a thick coat of wooly, golden brown hairs.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.mediterraneangardensocietyarchive.org/40-phlomis.html |last=Filippi |first=Olivier |journal=The Mediterranean Garden (Journal of the Mediterranean Garden Society) |date=April 2005 |volume=40 |title=In Search of ''Phlomis'' Species in Southern Turkey|website=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers are yellow with 20-30 mm corolla, appear in April-May, and are carried in the leaf axils.<ref name=\"Filippi2007\"/>\n\nIn the wild, ''P. bourgaei'' grows in shrublands, oak scrubs, and pine woods, on serpentine and calcareous rocks.<ref name=\"Taylor1998\">{{Cite book |last=Taylor |first=Jim Mann |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/40499720 |title=''Phlomis'': the neglected genus. A guide for gardeners and horticulturists |date=1998 |publisher=J.M. Taylor |others=[[National Council for the Conservation of Plants and Gardens]] (NCCPG), Great Britain |isbn=0-9532413-0-0 |location=Westbury-on-Severn |oclc=40499720 }}</ref><ref name=\"Stasher2019\"/> In cultivation it requires a well-drained soil and an exposure with sun or partial shade, and tolerates limestone.<ref name=\"Filippi2007\"/>\n\n== Hybrids ==\n* ''Phlomis'' x ''termessi'' Davis (''Phlomis bourgaei'' Boiss.\u00a0x\u00a0''[[Phlomis lycia]]'' D. Don)<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Y\u00fczba\u015f\u0131o\u011flu |first=Ertu\u011frul |last2=Dadand\u0131 |first2=Mehmet Ya\u015far |last3=\u00d6zcan |first3=Sebahattin |date=2008-05-01 |title=Natural hybridization between ''Phlomis lycia'' D. Don \u00d7 ''P. bourgaei'' Boiss., (Lamiaceae) revealed by RAPD markers |url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10709-007-9177-y |journal=Genetica |language=en |volume=133 |issue=1 |pages=13\u201320 |doi=10.1007/s10709-007-9177-y |issn=1573-6857 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15352220}}\n\n[[Category:Lamiaceae]]\n[[Category:Shrubs]]\n[[Category:Flora of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Taxa described in 1879]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of flowering plants in the sage family Lamiaceae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Phlomis bourgaei-Clapiers-7645~2020 03 27.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Phlomis bourgaei'', flowers and leaves\n|genus = Phlomis\n|species = bourgaei\n|authority = [[Edmond Boissier|Boiss.]]\n|synonyms = \n* ''Phlomis schwarzii'' P.H.Davis\n}}\n'''''Phlomis bourgaei''''', the '''puckered gray-green Turkish phlomis''',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ogden|first=Scott|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_w_9TBFiSqgC&pg=PA59|title=Waterwise Plants for Sustainable Gardens: 200 Drought-Tolerant Choices for all Climates|last2=Ogden|first2=Lauren Springer|date=2011-11-03|publisher=Timber Press|isbn=978-1-60469-336-2|language=en}}</ref> is a [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] Lamiaceae, [[native plant|native]] to East [[Aegean Islands]] to South West [[Turkey]].<ref name=\"Filippi2007\">{{cite book |last=Filippi |first=Olivier |date=2007 |title=Pour un jardin sans arrosage (For a garden without irrigation) |location=Arles |publisher=Actes Sud |page=154 |language=fr |isbn=978-2-7427-6730-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Stasher2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://noellemace.blogspot.com/2019/01/phlomis-fruticosa-bourgaei.html|title=''Phlomis fruticosa'' 'Bourgaei'|last=Stasher|date=2019-01-26|website=Stasher|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Botanical name#Binary name|specific epithet]] ''bourgaei'' is a [[Patronym (taxonomy)#Naming process|taxonomic patronym]] honouring the French botanical traveller [[Eug\u00e8ne Bourgeau]] (1813-1877), who collected in [[Anatolia]], [[North Africa]], and [[North America]]. \n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Phlomis bourgaei-MNHN-P-P00738090.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Herbarium specimen of ''Phlomis bourgaei'', collected by Eug\u00e8ne Bourgeau in 1860.]]\nIt is a [[shrub]], [[evergreen]], growing to {{convert|1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} tall by {{convert|80|cm|ft|0|abbr=on}} wide. The foliage shows a pronounced [[seasonal dimorphism]]. In winter and spring, the large, gray-green leaves develop horizontally to maximize [[photosynthesis]] during the growing period. In summer, after the flowering, the big leaves fall and the plant then produces a new generation of smaller, undulated leaves, compressed against each other along the stems to reduce the area of sun exposure and limit [[evapotranspiration]]. These new leaves are covered with a thick coat of wooly, golden brown hairs.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.mediterraneangardensocietyarchive.org/40-phlomis.html |last=Filippi |first=Olivier |journal=The Mediterranean Garden (Journal of the Mediterranean Garden Society) |date=April 2005 |volume=40 |title=In Search of ''Phlomis'' Species in Southern Turkey|website=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers are yellow with 20-30 mm corolla, appear in April-May, and are carried in the leaf axils.<ref name=\"Filippi2007\"/>\n\nIn the wild, ''P. bourgaei'' grows in shrublands, oak scrubs, and pine woods, on serpentine and calcareous rocks.<ref name=\"Taylor1998\">{{Cite book |last=Taylor |first=Jim Mann |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/40499720 |title=''Phlomis'': the neglected genus. A guide for gardeners and horticulturists |date=1998 |publisher=J.M. Taylor |others=[[National Council for the Conservation of Plants and Gardens]] (NCCPG), Great Britain |isbn=0-9532413-0-0 |location=Westbury-on-Severn |oclc=40499720 }}</ref><ref name=\"Stasher2019\"/> In cultivation it requires a well-drained soil and an exposure with sun or partial shade, and tolerates limestone.<ref name=\"Filippi2007\"/>\n\n== Hybrids ==\n* ''Phlomis'' x ''termessi'' Davis (''Phlomis bourgaei'' Boiss.\u00a0x\u00a0''[[Phlomis lycia]]'' D. Don)<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Y\u00fczba\u015f\u0131o\u011flu |first=Ertu\u011frul |last2=Dadand\u0131 |first2=Mehmet Ya\u015far |last3=\u00d6zcan |first3=Sebahattin |date=2008-05-01 |title=Natural hybridization between ''Phlomis lycia'' D. Don \u00d7 ''P. bourgaei'' Boiss., (Lamiaceae) revealed by RAPD markers |url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10709-007-9177-y |journal=Genetica |language=en |volume=133 |issue=1 |pages=13\u201320 |doi=10.1007/s10709-007-9177-y |issn=1573-6857 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15352220}}\n\n[[Category:Lamiaceae]]\n[[Category:Shrubs]]\n[[Category:Flora of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Taxa described in 1879]]\n", "name_user": "Manudouz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Speciesbox \u2192 image upright.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phlomis_bourgaei"}
